<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-02-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-02-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="287" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d287">
                        <head>No. 287.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Nelson</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                        the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-02-01"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 1,
                                1872</date>. (Received February 23.)</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 510.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: During the last year I had frequent
                            occasion to employ my good offices with the Mexican government, on
                            behalf of English, French, and Austrian subjects, resident in this
                            republic, in the absence of a diplomatic or consular agent of either of
                            those powers, and especially <pb facs="0483" n="387" xml:id="pg_387"/>
                            in procuring for them “<hi rend="italic">cartas de matricula,”</hi> and
                            otherwise enabling them to comply with the recent laws on the subject of
                            foreign citizenship.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>THOMAS H. NELSON.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>